.sp 2
The badmin command is the administrative tool for LSF.
.sp 2

.SH Synopsis

.sp 2
\fBbadmin \fRsubcommand options
.sp 2
\fBbadmin\fR [\fB-h\fR | \fB-V\fR]
.SH Description

.sp 2
The badmin command provides a set of subcommands to control and
monitor LSF. If you do not include subcommands, the \fRbadmin\fR
command prompts for subcommands from the standard input.
.sp 2
Information about each subcommand is available through the -h
option.
.sp 2
The badmin subcommands include privileged and non-privileged
subcommands. Only root or LSF administrators can run privileged
subcommands. The following subcommands are privileged:
.sp 2
   diagnose
.br
   gpddebug
.br
   gpdrestart
.br
   gpdtime
.br
   hclose
.br
   hghostadd
.br
   hghostdel
.br
   hopen
.br
   hpower
.br
   mbddebug
.br
   mbdrestart
.br
   perflog
.br
   perfmon
.br
   qact
.br
   qclose
.br
   qinact
.br
   qopen
.br
   reconfig
.br
   security
.sp 2
The configuration file lsf.sudoers must be set to use the
privileged command hstartup by a non-root user.
.sp 2
All other commands are non-privileged commands and can be used by
any LSF user. If the \fBLSF_AUTH\fR parameter is not defined in
the lsf.conf file, privileged ports are used and the badmin
command must be installed because it needs to send the request
through a privileged port. The badmin executable file is
installed with the setuid flag turned on.
.sp 2
When you use subcommands for which multiple host names can be
specified, do not enclose the host names in quotation marks.
