.SH Usage

.sp 2
\fBckconfig [-v]\fR
.br
         Checks LSF configuration files that are located in the
         LSB_CONFDIR/cluster_name/configdir directory, and checks
         the LSF_ENVDIR/lsf.licensescheduler file.
.sp 2
         The \fBLSB_CONFDIR\fR variable is defined in the
         lsf.conf file, in \fBLSF_ENVDIR\fR or /etc (if
         \fBLSF_ENVDIR\fR is not defined).
.sp 2
         By default, the badmin ckconfig command displays only
         the result of the configuration file check. If warning
         errors are found, the badmin command prompts you to
         display detailed messages.
.sp 2
         \fB-v\fR
.br
                  Verbose mode. Displays detailed messages about
                  configuration file checking to stderr.
.sp 2
\fBdiagnose \fI<pend jobid>\fB ...\fR
.br
         Displays full pending reason list if
         \fBCONDENSE_PENDING_REASONS=Y\fR is set in the
         lsb.params file.
.sp 2
         badmin diagnose 1057
.br

.sp 2
\fBdiagnose -c jobreq [-f \fIsnapshot_file_name\fB] [-t xml | -t
json]\fR
.br
         UNIX only. Saves the current contents of the scheduler
         job bucket information into an XML or JSON snapshot file
         as raw data.
.sp 2
         Jobs are put into scheduling buckets based on resource
         requirements and different scheduling policies. Saving
         the contents into a snapshot file is useful for data
         analysis by parsing the file or by running a simple text
         search on its contents.
.sp 2
         This feature is helpful if you want to examine a sudden
         large performance impact on the scheduler. Use the
         snapshot file to identify any users with many buckets or
         large attribute values.
.sp 2
         You can use the following options:
.sp 2
         \fB-c jobreq\fR
.br
                  Required.
.sp 2
         \fB-f \fIfile_name\fB\fR
.br
                  Specifies a snapshot file in which to save the
                  information. It is either a file name, which is
                  located in the \fBDIAGNOSE_LOGDIR\fR directory,
                  or a full path file name. If the specified
                  snapshot file exists, it is overwritten with
                  the current information.
.sp 2
                  The default name for the snapshot file is
                  jobreq_\fI<hostname>\fR_\fI<dateandtime>\fR.\fI<format>\fR,
                  where \fI<format>\fR is xml or json, depending
                  on the specified format of the snapshot file.
.sp 2
                  The owner of the log file is the user who is
                  specified in the \fBLSF_ADMIN\fR parameter. The
                  log file permissions are the same as the
                  mbatchd daemon log permissions. Everyone has
                  read and execute access but the \fBLSF_ADMIN\fR
                  owner has write, read, and execute access.
.sp 2
         \fB-t xml | -t json\fR
.br
                  Specifies the format of the snapshot file.
                  Specify \fR-t xml\fR for the snapshot file to
                  be in XML format, or specify \fR-t json\fR for
                  the snapshot file to be in JSON format.
.sp 2
                  The default format for the snapshot file is
                  XML, and the extension of the snapshot file is
                  .xml. If the snapshot file is in JSON format,
                  the extension of the snapshot file is .json.
.sp 2
\fBdiagnose -c query [-f \fIlogfile_name\fB] [-d \fIminutes\fB] |
[-o]]\fR
.br
         This feature is helpful if an unexpected mbatchd query
         load causes the cluster to slow or fail to respond to
         requests. For example, many bjobs command queries might
         cause a high network load and prevent the mbatchd daemon
         from responding. Running this command with its options
         enables the mbatchd daemon to dump the query source
         information into a log file.
.sp 2
         The log file shows information about the source of
         queries for easier troubleshooting. The log file shows
         who made these requests, where the requests came from,
         and the data size of the query.
.sp 2
         You can also configure this feature by enabling the
         \fBDIAGNOSE_LOGDIR\fR and \fBENABLE_DIAGNOSE\fR
         parameters in the lsb.params file to log the entire
         query information as soon as the cluster starts.
         However, the dynamic settings from the command override
         the static parameter settings. Also, after the duration
         you specify to track the query information expires, the
         static diagnosis settings take effect.
.sp 2
         You can use the following options to dynamically set the
         time, specify a log file, and allow the mbatchd daemon
         to collect information:
.sp 2
         \fB-c query\fR
.br
                  Required.
.sp 2
         \fB-f\fR
.br
                  Specifies a log file in which to save the
                  information. It is either a file name, which is
                  located in the \fBDIAGNOSE_LOGDIR\fR directory,
                  or a full path file name.
.sp 2
                  The default name for the log file is
                  query_info.querylog.<\fIhost_name\fR>.
.sp 2
                  The owner of the log file is the user who is
                  specified in the \fBLSF_ADMIN\fR parameter. The
                  log file permissions are the same as mbatchd
                  daemon log permissions. Everyone has read and
                  execute access but the \fBLSF_ADMIN\fR user has
                  write, read, and execute access.
.sp 2
                  If you specify the log file in the lsb.params
                  file and then later specify a different log
                  file in the command line, the one in the
                  command line takes precedence. Logging
                  continues until the specified duration is over,
                  or until you stop dynamic logging. It then
                  switches back to the static log file location.
.sp 2
         \fB-d \fIminutes\fB\fR
.br
                  The duration in minutes you specify to track
                  the query information. The mbatchd daemon
                  reverts to static settings after the duration
                  is over, or until you stop it manually, restart
                  (with the badmin mbdrestart command), or
                  reconfigure (with badmin reconfig command). The
                  default value for this duration is infinite. By
                  default, query information is always logged.
.sp 2
         \fB-o\fR
.br
                  Turns off dynamic diagnosis (stop logging). If
                  the \fBENABLE_DIAGNOSE=query\fR parameter is
                  configured, it returns to the static
                  configuration.
.sp 2
\fBgpdckconfig [-v]\fR
.br
         Checks the global policy configuration file
         lsb.globalpolicies located in the
         LSB_CONFDIR/cluster_name/configdir directory.
.sp 2
         The \fBLSB_CONFDIR\fR variable is defined in the
         lsf.conf file, in \fBLSF_ENVDIR\fR or /etc (if
         \fBLSF_ENVDIR\fR is not defined).
.sp 2
         By default, the badmin gpdckconfig command displays only
         the result of the configuration file check. If warning
         errors are found, the badmin command prompts you to
         display detailed messages.
.sp 2
         You can run the badmin gpdckconfig command only on the
         management host or management candidate hosts in the
         Global Policy Daemon Cluster (GPD Cluster).
.sp 2
         \fB-v\fR
.br
                  Verbose mode. Displays detailed messages about
                  configuration file checking to stderr.
.sp 2
\fBgpddebug [-c \fIclass_name\fB ...] [-l \fIdebug_level\fB] [-f
\fIlogfile_name\fB] [-o]\fR
.br
         Sets the message log level for the gpolicyd daemon to
         include additional information in log files. You must be
         \fRroot\fR or the LSF administrator to use this command.
.sp 2
         If the command is used without any options, the
         following default values are used:
.sp 2
         \fB\fR\fIclass_name\fR\fB\fR
.br
                  Not defined (no additional classes are logged).
.sp 2
         \fB\fR\fIdebug_level\fR=0\fB\fR
.br
                  As specified but the \fRLOG_DEBUG\fR level in
                  the \fBLSF_LOG_MASK\fR parameter.
.sp 2
         \fB\fR\fIlogfile_name\fR\fB\fR
.br
                  Not defined (LSF system log file in the LSF
                  system log file directory, in the format
                  \fRgpolicyd.log.\fIhost_name\fR\fR).
.sp 2
         \fB-c \fIclass_name\fB ...\fR
.br
                  Specifies software classes for which debug
                  messages are to be logged.
.sp 2
                  By default, \fIclass_name\fR is not defined and
                  no additional classes are logged.
.sp 2
                  The format of \fIclass_name\fR is the name of a
                  class, or a list of class names separated by
                  spaces and enclosed in quotation marks. Classes
                  are also listed in the \fRlsf.h\fR header file.
.sp 2
                  The following log classes are supported:
.sp 2
                  \fB\fRLC_AUTH\fB\fR
.br
                           Log authentication messages.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fRLC_COMM\fB\fR
.br
                           Log communication messages.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fRLC_SYS\fB\fR
.br
                           Log system call messages.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fRLC_TRACE\fB\fR
.br
                           Log significant program walk steps.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fRLC_XDR\fB\fR
.br
                           Log everything that is transferred by
                           XDR.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fRLC_XDRVERSION\fB\fR
.br
                           Log messages for XDR version.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fRLC2_G_FAIR\fB\fR
.br
                           Log global fairshare messages.
.sp 2
         \fB-l \fIdebug_level\fB\fR
.br
                  Specifies level of detail in debug messages.
                  The higher the number, the more detail that is
                  logged. Higher levels include all lower levels.
.sp 2
                  \fIdebug_level\fR has the following values:
.sp 2
                  \fBDefault: \fR0\fB\fR
.br
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG\fR level in parameter
                           \fBLSF_LOG_MASK\fR.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fR0\fB\fR
.br
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG\fR level for parameter
                           \fBLSF_LOG_MASK\fR in the lsf.conf
                           file.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fR1\fB\fR
.br
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG1\fR level for extended
                           logging. A higher level includes lower
                           logging levels. For example, the
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG1\fR level includes the
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG\fR level.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fR2\fB\fR
.br
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG2\fR level for extended
                           logging. A higher level includes lower
                           logging levels. For example, the
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG2\fR level includes
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG1\fR and \fBLOG_DEBUG\fR
                           levels.
.sp 2
                  \fB\fR3\fB\fR
.br
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG3\fR level for extended
                           logging. A higher level includes lower
                           logging levels. For example, the
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG3\fR level includes
                           \fBLOG_DEBUG2\fR, \fBLOG_DEBUG1\fR,
                           and \fBLOG_DEBUG\fR levels.
.sp 2
         \fB-f \fIlogfile_name\fB\fR
.br
                  Specifies the name of the file into which
                  debugging messages are to be logged. A file
                  name with or without a full path can be
                  specified.
.sp 2
                  If a file name without a path is specified, the
                  file is saved in the LSF system log directory.
.sp 2
                  The name of the file that is created has the
                  following format:
.sp 2
                  \fR\fIlogfile_name\fR.gpolicyd.log\fI.host_name\fR\fR
.sp 2
                  On UNIX, if the specified path is not valid,
                  the log file is created in the /tmp directory.
.sp 2
                  On Windows, if the specified path is not valid,
                  no log file is created.
.sp 2
                  By default, \fIlogfile_name\fR is the current
                  LSF system log file in the LSF system log file
                  directory.
.sp 2
         \fB-o\fR
.br
                  Turns off temporary debug settings and resets
                  them to the daemon start state. The message log
                  level is reset back to the value of
                  \fBLSF_LOG_MASK\fR and classes are reset to the
                  value of \fBLSB_DEBUG_GPD\fR.
.sp 2
                  The log file is also reset back to the default
                  log file.
.sp 2
\fBgpdrestart [-v] [-f]\fR
.br
         Dynamically reconfigures LSF global policies and
         restarts the gpolicyd daemon.
.sp 2
         The global policy configuration file lsb.globalpolicies
         is checked for errors and the results are printed to
         stderr. If no errors are found, the lsb.globalpolicies
         file is reloaded and the gpolicyd daemon is restarted.
.sp 2
         If warning errors are found, the badmin command prompts
         you to display detailed messages. If unrecoverable
         errors are found, the gpolicyd daemon is not restarted,
         and the badmin command exits.
.sp 2
         You can run the badmin gpdrestart command only on the
         management host or management candidate hosts in the
         Global Policy Daemon Cluster (GPD Cluster).
.sp 2
         \fB-v \fR
.br
                  Verbose mode. Displays detailed messages about
                  the status of configuration files. All messages
                  from configuration checking are printed to
                  stderr.
.sp 2
         \fB-f\fR
.br
                  Disables interaction and proceeds with the
                  gpolicyd daemon restart if configuration files
                  contain no unrecoverable errors.
.sp 2
\fBgpdtime [-l \fItiming_level\fB] [-f \fIlogfile_name\fB]
[-o]\fR
.br
         Sets the timing level for the gpolicyd daemon to include
         extra timing information in log files. You must be
         \fRroot\fR or the LSF administrator to use this command.
.sp 2
         If the command is used without any options, the
         following default values are used:
.sp 2
         \fB\fR\fItiming_level\fR\fB\fR
.br
                  Not defined (timing information is recorded).
.sp 2
         \fB\fR\fIlogfile_name\fR\fB\fR
.br
                  Not defined (current LSF system log file in the
                  LSF system log file directory, in the format
                  \fRgpolicyd.log.\fIhost_name\fR\fR).
.sp 2
         \fB-l \fItiming_level\fB\fR
.br
                  Specifies the detail of timing information that
                  is included in log files. Timing messages
                  indicate the execution time of functions in the
                  software and are logged in milliseconds.
.sp 2
                  The following values are supported:
                  \fR1|2|3|4|5\fR
.sp 2
                  The higher the number, the more functions in
                  the software that are timed and whose execution
                  time is logged. The lower numbers include more
                  common software functions. Higher levels
                  include all lower levels.
.sp 2
                  By default no timing information is logged.
.sp 2
         \fB-f \fIlogfile_name\fB\fR
.br
                  Specify the name of the file into which timing
                  messages are to be logged. A file name with or
                  without a full path can be specified.
.sp 2
                  If a file name without a path is specified, the
                  file is saved in the LSF system log file
                  directory.
.sp 2
                  The name of the file that is created has the
                  following format:
.sp 2
                  logfile_name.gpolicyd.log.host_name
.sp 2
                  On UNIX, if the specified path is not valid,
                  the log file is created in the /tmp directory.
.sp 2
                  On Windows, if the specified path is not valid,
                  no log file is created.
.sp 2
                  \fBNote: \fRBoth timing and debug messages are
                  logged in the same files.
.sp 2
                  The default is the current LSF system log file
                  in the LSF system log file directory, in the
                  format gpolicyd.log.\fIhost_name\fR.
.sp 2
         \fB-o\fR
.br
                  Optional. Turns off temporary timing settings
                  and resets them to the daemon start state. The
                  timing level is reset back to the value of the
                  parameter for the corresponding daemon
                  (LSB_TIME_GPD).
.sp 2
                  The log file is also reset back to the default
                  log file.
.sp 2
\fBhclose [-C \fIcomment\fB] [-i "\fIlock_id\fR"]
[\fIhost_name\fB ... | \fIhost_group\fB ... | \fIcompute_unit\fB
 ... | all]\fR
.br
         Closes batch server hosts. Specify the names of any
         server hosts, host groups, or compute units. All batch
         server hosts are closed if the reserved word all is
         specified. If no argument is specified, the local host
         is assumed. A closed host does not accept any new jobs,
         but jobs that are already dispatched to the host are not
         affected. This behavior is different from a host closed
         by a window; all jobs on a host are suspended when a
         time window closes on the host.
.sp 2
         If the host is already closed, this command option has
         no effect unless you specify the -i option to attach a
         lock ID to the host.
.sp 2
         \fB-C \fIcomment\fB\fR
.br
                  Logs the text as an administrator comment
                  record to the lsb.events file. The maximum
                  length of the comment string is 512 characters.
.sp 2
                  If you close a host group or compute unit, each
                  member is displayed with the same comment
                  string.
.sp 2
                  You cannot use the badmin hopen command to open
                  a host that was borrowed through LSF resource
                  connector that is in \fRclosed_RC\fR status.
.sp 2
         \fB-i "\fIlock_id\fB"\fR
.br
                  Closes the host and attaches the specified lock
                  ID to the closed host. Each lock ID is a string
                  that can contain up to 128 alphanumeric and
                  underscore (\fR_\fR) characters. The keyword
                  all is reserved and cannot be used as the lock
                  ID. A closed host can have multiple lock IDs,
                  and the host remains closed until there are no
                  more lock IDs attached to the host.
.sp 2
                  Use -i together with the -C option to attach an
                  administrator message to the lock ID.
.sp 2
                  If you try to attach a lock ID that is already
                  attached to the host (even with a different
                  comment), the command fails for that host.
.sp 2
                  Use the badmin hopen -i command option to
                  remove one or more lock IDs from a host.
.sp 2
                  This allows multiple users to keep a host
                  closed for different reasons. For example,
                  userA might be updating an application while
                  userB is configuring the operating system. The
                  host remains closed until both users complete
                  their updates and open the host using their
                  specific lock IDs.
.sp 2
\fBhelp [\fIcommand\fB ...] | ? [\fIcommand\fB ...]\fR
.br
         Displays the syntax and functions of the specified
         commands.
.sp 2
\fBhghostadd [-C \fIcomment\fB] \fIhost_group\fB |
\fIcompute_unit\fB |\fIhost_name\fB [\fIhost_name\fB ...]\fR
.br
         If dynamic host configuration is enabled, dynamically
         adds hosts to a host group or compute unit. After the
         mbatchd daemon receives the host information from the
         LIM on the management host, it dynamically adds the host
         without triggering reconfiguration.
.sp 2
         After the host is added to the host group or compute
         unit, it is considered part of that group for scheduling
         decisions for newly submitted jobs and for existing
         pending jobs.
.sp 2
         This command fails if any of the specified host groups,
         compute units, or host names are not valid.
.sp 2
         \fBRestriction: \fRIf EGO-enabled SLA scheduling is
         configured through the \fBENABLE_DEFAULT_EGO_SLA\fR
